## Migration to .NET 8

### Key Breaking Change

**`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8.** `ThreadAbortException` will never be raised. Your entire cancellation/cleanup strategy must be replaced with `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait gracefully, then abandon if it won't stop
            var completed = await Task.WhenAny(
                _workerTask,
                Task.Delay(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)));

            if (completed != _workerTask)
            {
                // Log warning — task is hung; cannot force-kill in .NET 8
                // Consider: Environment.FailFast() or let process exit
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### If you must keep synchronous/blocking APIs

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **`Thread.Abort()` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | No equivalent exists. You *must* use cooperative cancellation. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → gone** | No longer meaningful; remove entirely. |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O without a `CancellationToken`, cancellation stalls. Refactor to accept tokens or use `Task.WaitAsync(token)`. |
| **`volatile bool` race** | Replace with `CancellationToken` — it's thread-safe, integrates with async, and unblocks `WaitHandle`-based waits. |
| **No force-kill option** | If code truly hangs, your only options are: let the process exit, use `Environment.FailFast()`, or isolate in a child process. |
| **ASP.NET Core hosting** | Consider inheriting from `BackgroundService` (in `Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting`) — it handles lifetime, DI, and `StoppingToken` for you. |

---

### Bonus: As a hosted service (recommended for ASP.NET Core / Worker Service)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }

    public override async Task StopAsync(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        // Framework calls this on shutdown; base handles cancellation
        await base.StopAsync(cancellationToken);
        FlushBuffers();
    }
}
```

Register with `builder.Services.AddHostedService<BackgroundProcessor>();`.
